Incremental net benefit in randomized clinical trials with quality-adjusted 
survival.

Willan AR(1), Chen EB, Cook RJ, Lin DY.

Author information:
(1)Program in Population Health Sciences, Research Centre, Hospital for Sick 
Children, 555 University Avenue, Toronto ON, M5G 1X8, Canada. 
willana@mcmaster.ca

Owing to induced dependent censoring, estimating mean costs and quality-adjusted 
survival in a cost-effectiveness comparison of two groups using standard 
life-table methods leads to biased results. In this paper we propose methods for 
estimating the difference in mean costs and the difference in mean 
effectiveness, together with their respective variances and covariance in the 
presence of dependent censoring. We consider the situation in which the measure 
of effectiveness is either the probability of surviving a duration of interest 
or mean quality-adjusted survival time over a duration of interest. The methods 
are illustrated in an example using an incremental net benefit analysis.

